# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: upstash-serverless
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] In computing, a **cache** (/kæʃ/ ⓘ *KASH*) is a hardware or software component that stores data so that future requests for that data can be served faster; the data stored in a cache might be the result of an earlier computation or a copy of data stored elsewhere.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] A **cache hit** occurs when the requested data can be found in a cache, while a **cache miss** occurs when it cannot.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Cache hits are served by reading data from the cache, which is faster than recomputing a result or reading from a slower data store; thus, the more requests that can be served from the cache, the faster the system performs.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] To be cost-effective, caches must be relatively small.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Nevertheless, caches are effective in many areas of computing because typical computer applications access data with a high degree of locality of reference.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Such access patterns exhibit temporal locality, where data is requested that has been recently requested, and spatial locality, where data is requested that is stored near data that has already been requested.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] In memory design, there is an inherent trade-off between capacity and speed because larger capacity implies larger size and thus greater physical distances for signals to travel causing propagation delays.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] There is also a tradeoff between high-performance technologies such as SRAM and cheaper, easily mass-produced commodities such as DRAM, flash, or hard disks.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] The buffering provided by a cache benefits one or both of latency and throughput (bandwidth).
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] A larger resource incurs a significant latency for access – e.g. it can take hundreds of clock cycles for a modern 4 GHz processor to reach DRAM.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] This is mitigated by reading large chunks into the cache, in the hope that subsequent reads will be from nearby locations and can be read from the cache.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Prediction or explicit prefetching can be used to guess where future reads will come from and make requests ahead of time; if done optimally, the latency is bypassed altogether.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] The use of a cache also allows for higher throughput from the underlying resource, by assembling multiple fine-grain transfers into larger, more efficient requests.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] In the case of DRAM circuits, the additional throughput may be gained by using a wider data bus.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Hardware implements cache as a block of memory for temporary storage of data likely to be used again.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Central processing units (CPUs), solid-state drives (SSDs) and hard disk drives (HDDs) frequently include hardware-based cache, while web browsers and web servers commonly rely on software caching.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] A cache is made up of a pool of entries.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Each entry has associated *data*, which is a copy of the same data in some *backing store*.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Each entry also has a *tag*, which specifies the identity of the data in the backing store of which the entry is a copy.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] When the cache client (a CPU, web browser, operating system) needs to access data presumed to exist in the backing store, it first checks the cache.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] If an entry can be found with a tag matching that of the desired data, the data in the entry is used instead.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] This situation is known as a **cache hit**.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] For example, a web browser program might check its local cache on disk to see if it has a local copy of the contents of a web page at a particular URL.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] In this example, the URL is the tag, and the content of the web page is the data.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] The percentage of accesses that result in cache hits is known as the **hit rate** or **hit ratio** of the cache.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] The alternative situation, when the cache is checked and found not to contain any entry with the desired tag, is known as a **cache miss**.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] This requires a more expensive access of data from the backing store.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Once the requested data is retrieved, it is typically copied into the cache, ready for the next access.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] During a cache miss, some other previously existing cache entry is typically removed in order to make room for the newly retrieved data.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] The heuristic used to select the entry to replace is known as the replacement policy.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] One popular replacement policy, least recently used (LRU), replaces the oldest entry, the entry that was accessed less recently than any other entry.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] More sophisticated caching algorithms also take into account the frequency of use of entries.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Cache writes must eventually be propagated to the backing store.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] The timing for this is governed by the *write policy*.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] A write-back cache is more complex to implement since it needs to track which of its locations have been written over and mark them as *dirty* for later writing to the backing store.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] The data in these locations are written back to the backing store only when they are evicted from the cache, a process referred to as a *lazy write*.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] For this reason, a read miss in a write-back cache may require two memory accesses to the backing store: one to write back the dirty data, and one to retrieve the requested data.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Other policies may also trigger data write-back.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] The client may make many changes to data in the cache, and then explicitly notify the cache to write back the data.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Consequently, a decision needs to be made for write misses: whether or not to load the data into the cache.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Entities other than the cache may change the data in the backing store, in which case the copy in the cache may become out-of-date or *stale*.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Alternatively, when the client updates the data in the cache, copies of that data in other caches will become stale.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Communication protocols between the cache managers that keep the data consistent are associated with cache coherence.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] On a cache read miss, caches with a *demand paging policy* read the minimum amount from the backing store.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] A typical demand-paging virtual memory implementation reads one page of virtual memory (often 4 KB) from disk into the disk cache in RAM.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] A typical CPU reads a single L2 cache line of 128 bytes from DRAM into the L2 cache, and a single L1 cache line of 64 bytes from the L2 cache into the L1 cache.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Caches with a prefetch input queue or more general *anticipatory paging policy* go further—they not only read the data requested, but guess that the next chunk or two of data will soon be required, and so prefetch that data into the cache ahead of time.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Anticipatory paging is especially helpful when the backing store has a long latency to read the first chunk and much shorter times to sequentially read the next few chunks, such as disk storage and DRAM.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] A few operating systems go further with a loader that always pre-loads the entire executable into RAM.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] A few caches go even further, not only pre-loading an entire file, but also starting to load other related files that may soon be requested, such as the page cache associated with a prefetcher or the web cache associated with link prefetching.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Small memories on or close to the CPU can operate faster than the much larger main memory.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Most CPUs since the 1980s have used one or more caches, sometimes in cascaded levels; modern high-end embedded, desktop and server microprocessors may have as many as six types of cache (between levels and functions).
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Some examples of caches with a specific function are the D-cache, I-cache and the translation lookaside buffer for the memory management unit (MMU).
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Earlier graphics processing units (GPUs) often had limited read-only texture caches and used swizzling to improve 2D locality of reference.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Cache misses would drastically affect performance, e.g. if mipmapping was not used.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Caching was important to leverage 32-bit (and wider) transfers for texture data that was often as little as 4 bits per pixel.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] As GPUs advanced, supporting general-purpose computing on graphics processing units and compute kernels, they have developed progressively larger and increasingly general caches, including instruction caches for shaders, exhibiting functionality commonly found in CPU caches.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] These caches have grown to handle synchronization primitives between threads and atomic operations, and interface with a CPU-style MMU.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Digital signal processors have similarly generalized over the years.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Earlier designs used scratchpad memory fed by direct memory access; modern DSPs often include a very similar set of caches to a CPU (e.g.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Modified Harvard architecture with shared L2, split L1 I-cache and D-cache).
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] A memory management unit (MMU) that fetches page table entries from main memory has a specialized cache, used for recording the results of virtual address to physical address translations.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] This specialized cache is called a translation lookaside buffer (TLB).
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Information-centric networking (ICN) is an approach to evolve the Internet infrastructure away from a host-centric paradigm, based on perpetual connectivity and the end-to-end principle, to a network architecture in which the focal point is identified information.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Due to the inherent caching capability of the nodes in an ICN, it can be viewed as a loosely connected network of caches, which has unique requirements for caching policies.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] However, ubiquitous content caching introduces the challenge to content protection against unauthorized access, which requires extra care and solutions.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Unlike proxy servers, in ICN the cache is a network-level solution.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Therefore, it has rapidly changing cache states and higher request arrival rates; moreover, smaller cache sizes impose different requirements on the content eviction policies.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] In particular, eviction policies for ICN should be fast and lightweight.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Various cache replication and eviction schemes for different ICN architectures and applications have been proposed.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] The time aware least recently used (TLRU) is a variant of LRU designed for the situation where the stored contents in cache have a valid lifetime.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] The algorithm is suitable in network cache applications, such as ICN, content delivery networks (CDNs) and distributed networks in general.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] TLRU introduces a new term: time to use (TTU).
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] TTU is a time stamp on content which stipulates the usability time for the content based on the locality of the content and information from the content publisher.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Owing to this locality-based time stamp, TTU provides more control to the local administrator to regulate in-network storage.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] In the TLRU algorithm, when a piece of content arrives, a cache node calculates the local TTU value based on the TTU value assigned by the content publisher.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] The local TTU value is calculated by using a locally defined function.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Once the local TTU value is calculated the replacement of content is performed on a subset of the total content stored in cache node.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] The TLRU ensures that less popular and short-lived content should be replaced with incoming content.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] The least frequent recently used (LFRU) cache replacement scheme combines the benefits of LFU and LRU schemes.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] LFRU is suitable for network cache applications, such as ICN, CDNs and distributed networks in general.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] In LFRU, the cache is divided into two partitions called privileged and unprivileged partitions.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] The privileged partition can be seen as a protected partition.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] If content is highly popular, it is pushed into the privileged partition.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Replacement of the privileged partition is done by first evicting content from the unprivileged partition, then pushing content from the privileged partition to the unprivileged partition, and finally inserting new content into the privileged partition.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] In the above procedure, the LRU is used for the privileged partition and an approximated LFU (ALFU) scheme is used for the unprivileged partition.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] The basic idea is to cache the locally popular content with the ALFU scheme and push the popular content to the privileged partition.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] In 2011, the use of smartphones with weather forecasting options was overly taxing AccuWeather servers; two requests from the same area would generate separate requests.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] An optimization by edge-servers to truncate the GPS coordinates to fewer decimal places meant that the cached results from a nearby query would be used.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] The number of to-the-server lookups per day dropped by half.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] While CPU caches are generally managed entirely by hardware, a variety of software manages other caches.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] The page cache in main memory is managed by the operating system kernel.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] While the disk buffer, which is an integrated part of the hard disk drive or solid state drive, is sometimes misleadingly referred to as *disk cache*, its main functions are write sequencing and read prefetching.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] High-end disk controllers often have their own on-board cache for the hard disk drive's data blocks.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Finally, a fast local hard disk drive can also cache information held on even slower data storage devices, such as remote servers (web cache) or local tape drives or optical jukeboxes; such a scheme is the main concept of hierarchical storage management.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Also, fast flash-based solid-state drives (SSDs) can be used as caches for slower rotational-media hard disk drives, working together as hybrid drives.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Web browsers and web proxy servers, either locally or at the Internet service provider (ISP), employ web caches to store previous responses from web servers, such as web pages and images.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Web caches reduce the amount of information that needs to be transmitted across the network, as information previously stored in the cache can often be re-used.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] This reduces bandwidth and processing requirements of the web server, and helps to improve responsiveness for users of the web.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Another form of cache is P2P caching, where the files most sought for by peer-to-peer applications are stored in an ISP cache to accelerate P2P transfers.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Similarly, decentralised equivalents exist, which allow communities to perform the same task for P2P traffic, for example, Corelli.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] A cache can store data that is computed on demand rather than retrieved from a backing store.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Memoization is an optimization technique that stores the results of resource-consuming function calls within a lookup table, allowing subsequent calls to reuse the stored results and avoid repeated computation.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] It is related to the dynamic programming algorithm design methodology, which can also be thought of as a means of caching.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] A content delivery network (CDN) is a network of distributed servers that deliver pages and other web content to a user, based on the geographic locations of the user, the origin of the web page and the content delivery server.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] CDNs were introduced in the late 1990s as a way to speed up the delivery of static content, such as HTML pages, images and videos.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] By replicating content on multiple servers around the world and delivering it to users based on their location, CDNs can significantly improve the speed and availability of a website or application.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] When a user requests a piece of content, the CDN will check to see if it has a copy of the content in its cache.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] If it does, the CDN will deliver the content to the user from the cache.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] A cloud storage gateway is a hybrid cloud storage device that connects a local network to one or more cloud storage services, typically object storage services such as Amazon S3.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] It provides a cache for frequently accessed data, providing high speed local access to frequently accessed data in the cloud storage service.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Cloud storage gateways also provide additional benefits such as accessing cloud object storage through traditional file serving protocols as well as continued access to cached data during connectivity outages.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] A DNS cache caches a mapping of domain names to IP addresses.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Examples of services providing such caches include the BIND daemon and caching DNS resolver libraries.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Write-through operation is common when operating over unreliable networks, because of the enormous complexity of the coherency protocol required between multiple write-back caches when communication is unreliable.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] For instance, web page caches and client-side caches for distributed file systems (like those in NFS or SMB) are typically read-only or write-through specifically to keep the network protocol simple and reliable.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Web search engines also frequently make web pages they have indexed available from their cache.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] This can prove useful when web pages from a web server are temporarily or permanently inaccessible.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Database caching can substantially improve the throughput of database applications, for example in the processing of indexes, data dictionaries, and frequently used subsets of data.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] A distributed cache uses networked hosts to provide scalability, reliability and performance to the application.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] The hosts can be co-located or spread over different geographical regions.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Android Runtime and Common Language Runtime are examples that utilize storage-based JIT caches.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] GPU drivers usually utilize storage-based shader caches.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] The semantics of a *buffer* and a *cache* are not totally different; even so, there are fundamental differences in intent between the process of caching and the process of buffering.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Fundamentally, caching realizes a performance increase for transfers of data that is being repeatedly transferred.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] With read caches, a data item must have been fetched from its residing location at least once in order for subsequent reads of the data item to realize a performance increase by virtue of being able to be fetched from the cache's faster intermediate storage rather than the data's residing location.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Contrary to strict buffering, a caching process must adhere to a potentially distributed cache coherency protocol in order to maintain consistency between the cache's intermediate storage and the location where the data resides.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Buffering, on the other hand, reduces the number of transfers for otherwise novel data amongst communicating processes, which amortizes the overhead involved for several small transfers over fewer, larger transfers.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] It also provides an intermediary for communicating processes that are incapable of direct transfers amongst each other, or ensures a minimum data size or representation required by at least one of the communicating processes involved in a transfer.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] With typical caching implementations, a data item that is read or written for the first time is effectively being buffered.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Caching almost always involves some form of buffering, while strict buffering does not necessarily involve caching.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] A buffer is a temporary memory location that is traditionally used because CPU instructions cannot directly address data stored in peripheral devices.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Thus, addressable memory is used as an intermediate stage.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Additionally, such a buffer may be required when a large block of data is assembled or disassembled (as required by a storage device), or when data may be delivered in a different order than that in which it is produced.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Also, a whole buffer of data is usually transferred sequentially (for example, to hard disk), so buffering itself sometimes increases transfer performance or reduces the variation or jitter of the transfer's latency as opposed to caching where the intent is to reduce the latency.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] These benefits are present even if the buffered data are written to the buffer once and read from the buffer once.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] A cache also increases transfer performance.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] A part of the increase similarly comes from the possibility that multiple small transfers will be combined into one large transfer.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] But the main performance gain occurs because there is a good chance that the same data will be read from cache multiple times, or that written data will soon be read.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] A cache's sole purpose is to reduce accesses to the underlying slower storage.
[src:upstash-serverless/cache-computing] Cache is also usually an abstraction layer that is designed to be invisible from the perspective of neighboring layers.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] In computer science, a **data structure** is a way to organize and store data that is usually chosen for efficient access to data.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] More precisely, a data structure is the physical implementation of a data type, including specifications of the data organization and storage format, as well functions or operations for working with this data.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] Data structures are closely related to abstract data types (ADTs).
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] The data structure describes the representation of data in memory and how operations are carried out, while the ADT describes the logical form or algebraic structure of the data type—what operations are allowed and what results they produce—without describing how those operations are implemented.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] Some authors do not use the term "abstract data type" and simply refer to the logical and physical forms of the data structure.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] Efficient data structures are essential for managing large datasets and are fundamental to algorithm design.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] Relational databases commonly use B-tree indice for data retrieval, while compiler implementations usually use hash tables to look up identifiers.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] Filesystems and search engines make extensive use of specialized data structures.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] Rob Pike has stated that the choice of data structure almost always has a greater impact on efficiency than the choice of algorithm, as the algorithm is often self-evident.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] Data structures are used to organize data in both primary memory (RAM) and secondary storage (such as disks).
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] Implementing a data structure involves writing a set of subroutines—such as insertion, deletion, traversal, or lookup—that create and manipulate instances of that structure.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] Data structures can be implemented using a variety of programming languages and techniques.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] A data structure corresponds directly to a single concrete implementation, in contrast to an ADT which describes behavior and operations independently of any particular implementation.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] There may be multiple concrete data structures for the same ADT, for example a linked list or a resizable array for the list ADT.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] As such, the efficiency of a data structure is closely tied to its concrete implementation, and must be evaluated through benchmarks and theoretical simulation.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] Data structures generally rely on the ability of a computer to store and access data via memory addresses (as specified by a pointer—a bit string—or more abstractly via references) that can be itself stored in memory and manipulated by the program.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] For example, arrays and records store elements in contiguous memory locations, requiring a rigid layout but allowing fast indexed access by computing the address through arithmetic operations.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] In contrast, linked data structures (such as linked lists and trees) store addresses of related elements within their structure, enabling flexible memory usage and dynamic resizing.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] These different methods of data structuring come with different tradeoffs and are suited to different tasks.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] For instance, the contiguous memory allocation in arrays facilitates rapid access and modification operations, leading to optimized performance in sequential data processing scenarios.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] There are numerous types of data structures, generally built upon simpler primitive data types.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] Most assembly languages and some low-level languages, such as BCPL (Basic Combined Programming Language), lack built-in support for data structures.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] On the other hand, many high-level programming languages and some higher-level assembly languages, such as MASM, have special syntax or other built-in support for certain data structures, such as records and arrays.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] For example, the C (a direct descendant of BCPL) and Pascal languages support structs and records, respectively, in addition to vectors (one-dimensional arrays) and multi-dimensional arrays.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] Most programming languages feature some sort of library mechanism that allows data structure implementations to be reused by different programs.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] Modern languages usually come with standard libraries that implement the most common data structures.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] Examples are the C++ Standard Template Library, the Java Collections Framework, and the Microsoft .NET Framework.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] Modern languages also generally support modular programming, the separation between the interface of a library module and its implementation.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] Some provide opaque data types that allow clients to hide implementation details.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] Object-oriented programming languages, such as C++, Java, and Smalltalk, typically use classes for this purpose.
[src:upstash-serverless/data-structure] Many known data structures have concurrent versions which allow multiple computing threads to access a single concrete instance of a data structure simultaneously.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] An **in-memory database** (**IMDb**, or **main memory database system** (**MMDB**) or **memory resident database**) is a database management system that primarily relies on main memory for computer data storage.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] It is contrasted with database management systems that employ a disk storage mechanism.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] In-memory databases are faster than disk-optimized databases because disk access is slower than memory access and the internal optimization algorithms are simpler and execute fewer CPU instructions.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] Accessing data in memory eliminates seek time when querying the data, which provides faster and more predictable performance than disk.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] Applications where response time is critical, such as those running telecommunications network equipment and mobile advertising networks, often use main-memory databases.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] IMDBs have gained much traction, especially in the data analytics space, starting in the mid-2000s – mainly due to multi-core processors that can address large memory and due to less expensive RAM.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] A potential technical hurdle with in-memory data storage is the volatility of RAM.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] Specifically in the event of a power loss, intentional or otherwise, data stored in volatile RAM is lost.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] With the introduction of non-volatile random-access memory technology, in-memory databases will be able to run at full speed and maintain data in the event of power failure.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] In its simplest form, main memory databases store data on volatile memory devices.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] These devices lose all stored information when the device loses power or is reset.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] In this case, IMDBs can be said to lack support for the "durability" portion of the ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) properties.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] Volatile memory-based IMDBs can, and often do, support the other three ACID properties of atomicity, consistency and isolation.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] While storing data in-memory confers performance advantages, it is an expensive method of data storage.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] An approach to realising the benefits of in-memory storage while limiting its costs is to store the most frequently accessed data in-memory and the rest on disk.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] Since there is no hard distinction between which data should be stored in-memory and which should be stored on disk, some systems dynamically update where data is stored based on the data's usage.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] This approach is subtly different from caching, in which the most *recently accessed* data is cached, as opposed to the most *frequently accessed* data being stored in-memory.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] In the cloud computing industry the terms "data temperature", or "hot data" and "cold data" have emerged to describe how data is stored in this respect.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] Hot data is used to describe mission-critical data that needs to be accessed frequently while cold data describes data that is needed less often and less urgently, such as data kept for archiving or auditing purposes.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] Hot data should be stored in ways offering fast retrieval and modification, often accomplished by in-memory storage but not always.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] Cold data on the other hand can be stored in a more cost-effective way and is accepted that data access will likely be slower compared to hot data.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] While these descriptions are useful, "hot" and "cold" lack concrete definitions.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] Manufacturing efficiency provides another reason for selecting a combined in-memory/on-disk database system.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] Some device product lines, especially in consumer electronics, include some units with permanent storage, and others that rely on memory for storage (set-top boxes, for example).
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] If such devices require a database system, a manufacturer can adopt a hybrid database system at lower and *upper* cost, and with less customization of code, rather than using separate in-memory and on-disk databases, respectively, for its disk-less and disk-based products.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] The first database engine to support both in-memory and on-disk tables in a single database, WebDNA, was released in 1995.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] Another variation involves large amounts of nonvolatile memory in the server, for example, flash memory chips as addressable memory rather than structured as disk arrays.
[src:upstash-serverless/in-memory-database] A database in this form of memory combines very fast access speed with persistence over reboots and power losses.
[src:upstash-serverless/rate-limiting] In computer networks, **rate limiting** is used to control the rate of requests sent or received by a network interface controller.
[src:upstash-serverless/rate-limiting] It can be used to prevent DoS attacks and limit web scraping.
[src:upstash-serverless/rate-limiting] Research indicates flooding rates for one zombie machine are in excess of 20 HTTP GET requests per second, legitimate rates much less.
[src:upstash-serverless/rate-limiting] Rate limiting should be used along with throttling pattern to minimize the number of throttling errors.
[src:upstash-serverless/rate-limiting] Hardware appliances can limit the rate of requests on layer 4 or 5 of the OSI model.
[src:upstash-serverless/rate-limiting] Rate limiting can be induced by the network protocol stack of the sender due to a received ECN-marked packet and also by the network scheduler of any router along the way.
[src:upstash-serverless/rate-limiting] While a hardware appliance can limit the rate for a given range of IP-addresses on layer 4, it risks blocking a network with many users which are masked by NAT with a single IP address of an ISP.
[src:upstash-serverless/rate-limiting] Deep packet inspection can be used to filter on the session layer but will effectively disarm encryption protocols like TLS and SSL between the appliance and the protocol server (i.e. web server).
[src:upstash-serverless/rate-limiting] Protocol servers using a request / response model, such as FTP servers or typically Web servers may use a central in-memory key-value database, like Redis or Aerospike, for session management.
[src:upstash-serverless/rate-limiting] A rate limiting algorithm is used to check if the user session (or IP address) has to be limited based on the information in the session cache.
[src:upstash-serverless/rate-limiting] In case a client made too many requests within a given time frame, HTTP servers can respond with status code 429: Too Many Requests.
[src:upstash-serverless/rate-limiting] However, in some cases (i.e. web servers) the session management and rate limiting algorithm should be built into the application (used for dynamic content) running on the web server, rather than the web server itself.
[src:upstash-serverless/rate-limiting] When a protocol server or a network device notice that the configured request limit is reached, then it will offload new requests and not respond to them.
[src:upstash-serverless/rate-limiting] Sometimes they may be added to a queue to be processed once the input rate reaches an acceptable level, but at peak times the request rate can even exceed the capacities of such queues and requests have to be thrown away.
[src:upstash-serverless/rate-limiting] Data centers widely use rate limiting to control the share of resources given to different tenants and applications according to their service level agreement.
[src:upstash-serverless/rate-limiting] A variety of rate limiting techniques are applied in data centers using software and hardware.
[src:upstash-serverless/rate-limiting] Virtualized data centers may also apply rate limiting at the hypervisor layer.
[src:upstash-serverless/rate-limiting] Two important performance metrics of rate limiters in data centers are resource footprint (memory and CPU usage) which determines scalability, and precision.
[src:upstash-serverless/rate-limiting] There usually exists a trade-off, that is, higher precision can be achieved by dedicating more resources to the rate limiters.
[src:upstash-serverless/rate-limiting] A considerable body of research with focus on improving performance of rate limiting in data centers.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] The project was developed and maintained by Salvatore Sanfilippo, starting in 2009.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] From 2015 until 2020, he led a project core team sponsored by Redis Labs.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Salvatore Sanfilippo left Redis as the maintainer in 2020.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] In 2021 Redis Labs dropped the Labs from its name and now is known simply as "Redis".
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] In 2018, some modules for Redis adopted a modified Apache 2.0 license with a Commons Clause.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] In 2024, the main Redis code switched from the open-source BSD-3 license to being dual-licensed under the Redis Source Available License v2 and the Server Side Public License v1.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] On May 1, 2025, Redis became tri-licensed beginning with version 8.0, with the GNU Affero General Public License as the third option.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] The name *Redis* means Remote Dictionary Server.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] The Redis project began when Salvatore Sanfilippo (nicknamed *antirez*) was trying to improve the scalability of his Italian startup and developed a real-time web log analyzer.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] After encountering significant problems in scaling some types of workloads using traditional database systems, Sanfilippo began in 2009 to prototype a first proof of concept version of Redis in Tcl.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Later, Sanfilippo translated that prototype to the C language and implemented the first data type, the list.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] After a few weeks of using the project internally with success, Sanfilippo decided to open source it, announcing the project on Hacker News.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] The project began to get traction, particularly among the Ruby community, with GitHub and Instagram being among the first companies adopting it.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Sanfilippo was hired by VMware in March 2010.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] In May 2013, Redis was sponsored by Pivotal Software (a VMware spin-off).
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] In June 2015, development became sponsored by Redis Ltd.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] This made the modules source-available and no longer free software.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] The core Redis software remained under a BSD license, with Redis Ltd. committing to maintaining these terms.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] In October 2018, Redis 5.0 was released, introducing Redis Stream – a new data structure that allows storage of multiple fields and string values with an automatic, time-based sequence at a single key.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] In June 2020, Salvatore Sanfilippo stepped down as Redis' sole maintainer.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Sanfilippo was succeeded by Yossi Gottlieb and Oran Agra.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] In March 2024, Redis Ltd. announced that beginning with version 7.4, the core Redis software would be relicensed under the RSAL and Server Side Public License (SSPL), both of which are source-available and non-free.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] The Linux Foundation subsequently announced that it would fork the last BSD-licensed version of Redis as Valkey.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] In May 2025, Redis Ltd. announced that it would change the license again to the AGPL beginning on version 8.0, citing that forks had achieved their goal of creating a "level playing field" of differentiated products, and that Redis has achieved "record growth" since the change in license.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Sanfilippo returned to Redis in December 2024.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Redis is a system that functions as both a data store and a cache.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Data is modified and read from the main computer memory while also being persisted to disk in a format optimized for sequential access rather than random access.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] The formatted data is only reconstructed into memory once the system restarts.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Redis uses a data model that differs from relational database management system (RDBMS).
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Commands specify operations on abstract data types rather than queries to be executed by a database engine.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Data is stored in structures designed for direct retrieval.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] It does not rely on secondary indexes, aggregations, or other features common in traditional RDBMS.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] The Redis implementation uses the fork system call to duplicate the process holding the data.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] This allows the parent process to continue serving clients while the child process persists the in-memory data to disk.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Redis supports a number of data types including Strings, JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) documents, Hashes (a collection of fields, each field is a name-value string pair), lists, sets, vector sets, and more.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] The Redis Query Engine allows users to use Redis as a document database, a vector database, a secondary index, and a search engine.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] With Redis Query Engine, users can define indexes for hash and JSON documents, and use a rich query language for vector search, full-text search, geospatial queries, and aggregations.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Redis Pub/Sub (short for publish/subscribe) is a lightweight messaging capability.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Publishers send messages to a channel, and subscribers receive messages from that channel.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] A Redis transaction allows the execution of a group of commands in a single step.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] A request sent by another client will never be served during the execution of a transaction.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] This guarantees that the commands are executed as a single isolated operation.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Redis users can also upload and execute Lua scripts on the server.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] As of May 1, 2025, for all version of Redis starting with 8.0, all data types are included in the same package and available under the Redis Source Available license v2.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Previously some data types were separate and therefore available under difference licenses.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Redis typically holds the whole dataset in memory.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Versions up to 2.4 could be configured to use what they refer to as virtual memory in which some of the dataset is stored on disk, but this feature is deprecated.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Redis can rewrite the append-only file in the background to avoid an indefinite growth of the journal.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Journaling was introduced in version 1.1 and is generally considered the safer approach.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] By default, Redis writes data to a file system at least every two seconds, with more or less robust options available if needed.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] In the case of a complete system failure on default settings, only a few seconds of data will be lost.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Redis supports master–replica replication.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Data from any Redis server can replicate to any number of replicas.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] A replica may be a master to another replica.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] This allows Redis to implement a single-rooted replication tree.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Redis replicas can be configured to accept writes, permitting intentional and unintentional inconsistency between instances.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] The publish–subscribe feature is fully implemented, so a client of a replica may subscribe to a channel and receive a full feed of messages published to the master, anywhere up the replication tree.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Replication is useful for read (but not write) scalability or data redundancy.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] When the durability of data is not needed, the in-memory nature of Redis allows it to perform well compared to database systems that write every change to disk before considering a transaction committed.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Redis operates as a single process and is single-threaded or double-threaded when it rewrites the AOF (append-only file).
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Thus, a single Redis instance cannot use parallel execution of tasks such as stored procedures.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Redis introduced clustering in April 2015 with the release of version 3.0.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] The cluster specification implements a subset of Redis commands: all single-key commands are available, multi-key operations (commands related to unions and intersections) are restricted to keys belonging to the same node, and commands related to database selection operations are unavailable.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] A Redis cluster can scale up to 1,000 nodes, achieve "acceptable" write safety and to continue operations when some nodes fail.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Redis has been used by Adobe, Airbnb, Amazon, Hulu, OpenAI, Salesforce, Shopify, Tinder, Twitter, and Yahoo.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Typical use cases of Redis are session caching, full page cache, message queue applications, leaderboards and counting among others.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] The publish–subscribe messaging paradigm allows real-time communication between servers.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Amazon Web Services offers a managed Redis service called ElastiCache for Redis, Google offers a managed Redis service called Cloud Memorystore, Microsoft offers Azure Cache for Redis in Azure, and Alibaba offers ApsaraDB for Redis in Alibaba Cloud.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] Redis is interfaced with by various libraries.
[src:upstash-serverless/redis] For example, POCO C++ Libraries supports interfacing with Redis through its `Poco::Redis` library.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] Serverless computing does not eliminate complexity but shifts much of it from the operations team to the development team.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] However, this shift is not absolute, as operations teams continue to manage aspects such as identity and access management (IAM), networking, security policies, and cost optimization.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] Additionally, while breaking down applications into finer-grained components can increase management complexity, the relationship between granularity and management difficulty is not strictly linear.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] There is often an optimal level of modularization where the benefits outweigh the added management overhead.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] According to Yan Cui, serverless techniques should be adopted only when they help to deliver customer value faster.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] And while adopting, organizations should take small steps and de-risk along the way.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] Serverless applications are prone to fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] Monitoring and debugging serverless applications can present unique challenges due to their distributed, event-driven nature and proprietary environments.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] Traditional tools may fall short, making it difficult to track execution flows across services.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] However, modern solutions such as distributed tracing tools (e.g., AWS X-Ray, Datadog), centralized logging, and cloud-agnostic observability platforms are mitigating these challenges.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] Emerging technologies like OpenTelemetry, AI-powered anomaly detection, and serverless-specific frameworks are further improving visibility and root cause analysis.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] While challenges persist, advancements in monitoring and debugging tools are steadily addressing these limitations.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] According to OWASP, serverless applications are vulnerable to variations of traditional attacks, insecure code, and some serverless-specific attacks (like *denial of wallet*).
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] So, the risks have changed and attack prevention requires a shift in mindset.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] Serverless computing is provided as a third-party service.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] Applications and software that run in the serverless environment are by default locked to a specific cloud vendor.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] This issue is exacerbated in serverless computing, as with its increased level of abstraction, public vendors only allow customers to upload code to a FaaS platform without the authority to configure underlying environments.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] More importantly, when considering a more complex workflow that includes backend-as-a-service (BaaS), a BaaS offering can typically only natively trigger a FaaS offering from the same provider.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] This makes the workload migration in serverless computing virtually impossible.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] Therefore, considering how to design and deploy serverless workflows from a multi-cloud perspective could mitigate this.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] Serverless computing may not be ideal for certain high-performance computing (HPC) workloads due to resource limits often imposed by cloud providers, including maximum memory, CPU, and runtime restrictions.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] For workloads requiring sustained or predictable resource usage, bulk-provisioned servers can sometimes be more cost-effective than the pay-per-use model typical of serverless platforms.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] However, serverless computing is increasingly capable of supporting specific HPC workloads, particularly those that are highly parallelizable and event-driven, by leveraging its scalability and elasticity.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] The suitability of serverless computing for HPC continues to evolve with advancements in cloud technologies.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] The *grain of sand* anti-pattern refers to the creation of excessively small components (e.g., functions) within a system, often resulting in increased complexity, operational overhead, and performance inefficiencies.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] *Lambda pinball* is a related anti-pattern that can occur in serverless architectures when functions (e.g., AWS Lambda, Azure functions) excessively invoke each other in fragmented chains, leading to latency, debugging and testing challenges, and reduced observability.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are associated with the formation of a distributed monolith.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] These anti-patterns are often addressed through the application of clear domain boundaries, which distinguish between public and published interfaces.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] Public interfaces are technically accessible interfaces, such as methods, classes, API endpoints, or triggers, but they do not come with formal stability guarantees.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] In contrast, published interfaces involve an explicit stability contract, including formal versioning, thorough documentation, a defined deprecation policy, and often support for backward compatibility.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] Published interfaces may also require maintaining multiple versions simultaneously and adhering to formal deprecation processes when breaking changes are introduced.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] Fragmented chains of function calls are often observed in systems where serverless components (functions) interact with other resources in complex patterns, sometimes described as spaghetti architecture or a distributed monolith.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] In contrast, systems exhibiting clearer boundaries typically organize serverless components into cohesive groups, where internal public interfaces manage inter-component communication, and published interfaces define communication across group boundaries.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] This distinction highlights differences in stability guarantees and maintenance commitments, contributing to reduced dependency complexity.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] Additionally, patterns associated with excessive serverless function chaining are sometimes addressed through architectural strategies that emphasize native service integrations instead of individual functions, a concept referred to as the functionless mindset.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] However, this approach is noted to involve a steeper learning curve, and integration limitations may vary even within the same cloud vendor ecosystem.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] Reporting on serverless databases presents challenges, as retrieving data for a reporting service can either break the bounded contexts, reduce the timeliness of the data, or do both.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] This applies regardless of whether data is pulled directly from databases, retrieved via HTTP, or collected in batches.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] Mark Richards refers to this as the *reach-in reporting* anti-pattern.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] A possible alternative to this approach is for databases to asynchronously push the necessary data to the reporting service instead of the reporting service pulling it.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] While this method requires a separate contract between services and the reporting service and can be complex to implement, it helps preserve bounded contexts while maintaining a high level of data timeliness.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] Adopting DevSecOps practices can help improve the use and security of serverless technologies.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] In serverless applications, the distinction between infrastructure and business logic is often blurred, with applications typically distributed across multiple services.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] To maximize the effectiveness of testing, integration testing is emphasized for serverless applications.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] Additionally, to facilitate debugging and implementation, orchestration is used within the bounded context, while choreography is employed between different bounded contexts.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] Ephemeral resources are typically kept together to maintain high cohesion.
[src:upstash-serverless/serverless-computing] However, shared resources with long spin-up times, such as AWS RDS clusters and landing zones, are often managed in separate repositories, deployment pipeline, and stacks.
